defs.name: Stats
defs.docs: Trait that provides simple descriptive statistics on a univariate set of numeric samples.

defs.name: sum
defs.docs: Sum of the samples.

defs.name: min
defs.docs: Minimum value of the samples.

defs.name: max
defs.docs: Maximum value of the samples.

defs.name: mean
defs.docs: Arithmetic mean (average) of the samples: sum divided by sample-count.

defs.name: median
defs.docs:
Median of the samples: value separating the lower half of the samples from the higher half.
 Equal to `self.percentile(50.0)`.

defs.name: var
defs.docs:
Variance of the samples: bias-corrected mean of the squares of the differences of each
 sample from the sample mean. Note that this calculates the _sample variance_ rather than the
 population variance, which is assumed to be unknown. It therefore corrects the `(n-1)/n`
 bias that would appear if we calculated a population variance, by dividing by `(n-1)` rather
 than `n`.

defs.name: std_dev
defs.docs: Standard deviation: the square root of the sample variance.

defs.name: std_dev_pct
defs.docs: Standard deviation as a percent of the mean value. See `std_dev` and `mean`.

defs.name: median_abs_dev
defs.docs:
Scaled median of the absolute deviations of each sample from the sample median. This is a
 robust (distribution-agnostic) estimator of sample variability. Use this in preference to
 `std_dev` if you cannot assume your sample is normally distributed. Note that this is scaled
 by the constant `1.4826` to allow its use as a consistent estimator for the standard
 deviation.

defs.name: median_abs_dev_pct
defs.docs: Median absolute deviation as a percent of the median. See `median_abs_dev` and `median`.

defs.name: percentile
defs.docs:
Percentile: the value below which `pct` percent of the values in `self` fall. For example,
 percentile(95.0) will return the value `v` such that 95% of the samples `s` in `self`
 satisfy `s <= v`.

defs.name: quartiles
defs.docs:
Quartiles of the sample: three values that divide the sample into four equal groups, each
 with 1/4 of the data. The middle value is the median. See `median` and `percentile`. This
 function may calculate the 3 quartiles more efficiently than 3 calls to `percentile`, but
 is otherwise equivalent.

defs.name: iqr
defs.docs:
Inter-quartile range: the difference between the 25th percentile (1st quartile) and the 75th
 percentile (3rd quartile). See `quartiles`.

defs.name: Summary
defs.value: Summary { sum, min, max, mean, median, var, std_dev, std_dev_pct, median_abs_dev, median_abs_dev_pct, quartiles, iqr }
defs.docs: Extracted collection of all the summary statistics of a sample set.

defs.name: new
defs.docs: Construct a new summary of a sample set.

defs.name: winsorize
defs.docs:
Winsorize a set of samples, replacing values above the `100-pct` percentile
 and below the `pct` percentile with those percentiles themselves. This is a
 way of minimizing the effect of outliers, at the cost of biasing the sample.
 It differs from trimming in that it does not change the number of samples,
 just changes the values of those that are outliers.

NOTE: We don't have a proper black box in stable Rust. This is
 a workaround implementation, that may have a too big performance overhead,
 depending on operation, or it may fail to properly avoid having code
 optimized out. It is good enough that it is used by default.
